        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1347807106" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8860328810885298839">A tremendous, beautiful piece of work. In the earlier sketches, the narrator (I&apos;ll say &quot;narrator&quot; because the book is labeled as fiction, though I believe it&apos;s pretty autobiographical) describes his peculiar, heart-wrenching childhood, growing up closeted in 50&apos;s suburbia. Then in the last chapters, he delivers the harrowing tale of his brother&apos;s demise. Mother of Sorrows is ultimately about family, I think -- the strong bonds between mothers and sons and brothers, for better or for worse. And M</span>
  <span id="freeText8860328810885298839" style="display:none">A tremendous, beautiful piece of work. In the earlier sketches, the narrator (I'll say "narrator" because the book is labeled as fiction, though I believe it's pretty autobiographical) describes his peculiar, heart-wrenching childhood, growing up closeted in 50's suburbia. Then in the last chapters, he delivers the harrowing tale of his brother's demise. Mother of Sorrows is ultimately about family, I think -- the strong bonds between mothers and sons and brothers, for better or for worse. And McCann is such an elegant writer, I can't recommend this book highly enough. </span>
